Enclosing class:
JsNode
public static class JsNode.Member
extends DOM2Core.Node.Prototype.Member

An opaque class representing members of its enclosing opaque type.

Note that, this class is opaque but its constructors are all internal. This class and the subclasses of this class are used to declare either opaque public instance fields of the opaque type Var.Member or the opaque public static fields of other opaque types while their constructors are used to define the fields inside opaque classes. Under either circumstance, the field names must be exactly same as the member names, as the opaque fields of opaque types are resolved by re-compilers directly based on the field names.

Author:
J.J.Liu (Jianjun Liu) at http://www.jscripter.org
JavaScript:
Opaque types can be resolved but no class objects for them can be created in the target codes. Re-compilers must exit with error on operations accessing that kind of class objects. Re-compilers must resolve an opaque instance field declared by this class in Var.Member or its subclasses to the JavaScript identifier: 
q.m
where m is the identifier of the field name and q is the identifier resolved from the instance of the enclosing member. Re-compilers must resolve an opaque static field declared by this class in opaque types other than Var.Member and its subclasses to the JavaScript identifier: 
m
where m is the identifier of the field name. And re-compilers must report error on the access to opaque fields declared by this class under any other circumstances.

Field Detail

attributes

public final JsArray.Member attributes

An opaque instance field defining a sub-member that is named by the name of this field, qualified by the current member instance of the field, and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsElement object refers to a read-only array of JsAttr nodes that represent the attributes of that element. Note that this array is live: any changes to the attributes of the element are immediately visible through it.

Technically, the array is of NamedNodeMap interface which is specified by the Level 1 DOM standard and defines a number of methods for querying, setting, and removing elements. JsElement defines better methods for setting and querying element attributes, and there are no other uses of NamedNodeMap that are relevant to client-side JavaScript. Treat the attributes property as a read-only array of JsAttr objects, or use the methods defined by JsElement to query, set, and delete attributes.

Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must resolve the member of this instance field to the identifier of the field name appending to the identifier resolved from its qualifying member with a dot in between.

childNodes

public final JsNodeList.Member<?> childNodes

An opaque instance field defining a sub-member that is named by the name of this field, qualified by the current member instance of the field, and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsNode object refers to a read-only array containing the child nodes of the current node. This property should never be null and for nodes with no children, the length of the array is zero. The property is actually a JsNodeList object, but it behaves just like a read-only array of JsNode objects. Note that the JsNodeList object is live: any changes to this element's list of children are immediately visible through the JsNodeList object.

Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must resolve the member of this instance field to the identifier of the field name appending to the identifier resolved from its qualifying member with a dot in between.

nodeName

public final Value.String.Member nodeName

An opaque instance field defining a sub-member that is named by the name of this field, qualified by the current member instance of the field, and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsNode object refers to a read-only string specifying the name of the node. For JsElement nodes, it specifies the tag name of the element, which can also be retrieved with the JsElement.tagName property. For other types of nodes, the value of nodeName depends on the node type:

  • JsNode.ELEMENT_NODE: The element's tag name.
  • JsNode.ATTRIBUTE_NODE: The attribute name.
  • JsNode.TEXT_NODE: "#text"
  • JsNode.CDATA_SECTION_NODE: "#cdata-section"
  • JsNode.PROCESSING_INSTRUCTION_NODE: The target of the PI.
  • JsNode.COMMENT_NODE: "#comment"
  • JsNode.DOCUMENT_NODE: "#document"
  • JsNode.DOCUMENT_TYPE_NODE: The document type name.
  • JsNode.DOCUMENT_FRAGMENT_NODE: "#document-fragment"

Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must resolve the member of this instance field to the identifier of the field name appending to the identifier resolved from its qualifying member with a dot in between.

nodeType

public final Value.Number.Member nodeType

An opaque instance field defining a sub-member that is named by the name of this field, qualified by the current member instance of the field, and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsNode object refers to a read-only integer value represents the type of the node specifying which sub-interface the node implements. The legal values are:

  • DOM2Core.Node.ELEMENT_NODE or JsNode.ELEMENT_NODE for JsElement nodes
  • DOM2Core.Node.ATTRIBUTE_NODE or JsNode.ATTRIBUTE_NODE for JsAttr nodes
  • DOM2Core.Node.TEXT_NODE or JsNode.TEXT_NODE for JsText nodes
  • DOM2Core.Node.CDATA_SECTION_NODE or JsNode.CDATA_SECTION_NODE for JsCDATASection nodes
  • DOM2Core.Node.PROCESSING_INSTRUCTION_NODE or JsNode.PROCESSING_INSTRUCTION_NODE for JsProcessingInstruction nodes
  • DOM2Core.Node.COMMENT_NODE or JsNode.COMMENT_NODE for JsComment nodes
  • DOM2Core.Node.DOCUMENT_NODE or JsNode.DOCUMENT_NODE for JsDocument nodes
  • DOM2Core.Node.DOCUMENT_TYPE_NODE or JsNode.DOCUMENT_TYPE_NODE for JsDocumentType nodes
  • DOM2Core.Node.DOCUMENT_FRAGMENT_NODE or JsNode.DOCUMENT_FRAGMENT_NODE for JsDocumentFragment nodes
For the compatibility with IE, you must use the static numeric literals JsClient.Node.

Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must resolve the member of this instance field to the identifier of the field name appending to the identifier resolved from its qualifying member with a dot in between.

nodeValue

public final Value.String.Member nodeValue

An opaque instance field defining a sub-member that is named by the name of this field, qualified by the current member instance of the field, and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsNode object refers to a read-only string specifying the value of the node. For JsText nodes, it holds the text content. For other types of nodes, the value depends on the value of nodeType:

  • JsNode.ELEMENT_NODE: null
  • JsNode.ATTRIBUTE_NODE: The attribute value.
  • JsNode.TEXT_NODE: The text of the node.
  • JsNode.CDATA_SECTION_NODE: The text of the node.
  • JsNode.PROCESSING_INSTRUCTION_NODE: The remainder of the PI.
  • JsNode.COMMENT_NODE: The text of the comment.
  • JsNode.DOCUMENT_NODE: null
  • JsNode.DOCUMENT_TYPE_NODE: null
  • JsNode.DOCUMENT_FRAGMENT_NODE: null

Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must resolve the member of this instance field to the identifier of the field name appending to the identifier resolved from its qualifying member with a dot in between.

Constructor Detail

JsNode.Member

public JsNode.Member(JsObject.Member q,
                     Var.Mid mid)

Internally constructs a member based on a qualifying member.

This constructor is internal and only called inside of opaque or internal classes or class members.

Note that, this constructor is internal but its declaring class is opaque. This constructor is used to define opaque instance fields declared in the declaring class of this constructor itself or its subclasses. Under this circumstance, the field names must be exactly same as the member names, as the opaque instance fields of the opaque type Var.Member or its subclasses are resolved by re-compilers directly to their names appending to the name resolved from the specified qualifying member with a dot in between.

Parameters:
q - A qualifying member
mid - The ID of the member to construct
Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must report error on the invocation to an internal constructor.

JsNode.Member

public JsNode.Member(Var.Mid mid)

Internally constructs a member without a qualifying member.

This constructor is internal and only called inside of opaque or internal classes or class members.

Note that, this constructor is internal but its declaring class is opaque. This constructor is used to define opaque static fields, declared in opaque types other than the declaring class of this constructor itself and its subclasses. Under this circumstance, the field names must be exactly same as the member names, as the opaque static fields of opaque types are generally resolved by re-compilers directly to identifiers of their names.

Parameters:
mid - The ID of the member to construct
Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must report error on the invocation to an internal constructor.
